It seems that it's not possible to associate several set C++ functions to one Python property. By example

```
class COverload
 {
 public:
	void setn(int n) {fprintf(stdout, "set n\n"); value = n;}
	void sets(std::string s) {fprintf(stdout, "set s\n"); value = atoi(s.c_str());}
	int get(void) {return value;}
 private:
	int value;
 };

...

	py::class_<COverload>(m, "Overload")
		.def(py::init<>())
		.def("set", &COverload::setn)
		.def("set", &COverload::sets)
		.def_property("attr", &COverload::get, &COverload::setn)
		.def_property("attr", &COverload::get, &COverload::sets);
```

In this case, the last property definition overwrite the previous one. So in Python, we can assign value using the set function with an integer or a string but only with a string when using the property attr.

I think it would be useful to allow several functions for setting a property because it's possible in Python to assign a property with different type of value. Is it possible to implement that?

The following program with a bogus implicit conversion exhibits curious behavior:

```cpp
#include <pybind11/pybind11.h>

namespace py = pybind11;

PYBIND11_MODULE(example, m) {
    struct A { A() { } };

    py::class_<A>(m, "A")
        .def(py::init<const A &>());

    py::implicitly_convertible<int, A>();
}
```

Test driver:
```python
import example
example.A(1)
```

The implicit conversion gets triggered again and again (due to the copy constructor) until the stack overflows.  On some platforms (Linux, OSX), Python seems to catch the stack overflow internally and throws an exception which then causes the implicit conversion to fail. After that, pybind11 just prints a normal parameter error, hiding the undesired program behavior that just transpired:

```
TypeError: __init__(): incompatible constructor arguments. The following argument types are supported:
    1. example.A(arg0: example.A)
```

On Windows + Python 2.7 (MSVC2017 debug mode), this seems to crash fairly reliably. (I stumbled across this issue while debugging an AppVeyor CI failure of a piece of software I develop. The implicit conversion was a lot more subtle in my case and additionally involved a custom type converter.)

Although one could argue that the infeasible implicit conversion is to blame for the problem here, I don't think that it should be allowed to trigger undefined behavior. 

One potential fix would be to disable implicit conversion by default when executing a copy constructor. I'm not sure about the best way to add that and wanted to bring it up for discussion:

One way would be to detect it at compile time -- for instance, the following seems to do the job:
```cpp
/// in common.h
template <typename T, typename... Args> struct is_copy_constructor : std::false_type { };
template <typename T> struct is_copy_constructor<T, T> : std::true_type { };

/// in init.h, constructor::Execute
constexpr bool copy_constructor = detail::is_copy_constructor<Cpp<Class>, intrinsic_t<Args>...>::value;
// now what?
```
This would need to be turned int some kind of attribute that gets passed into ``class_::def``, potentially using a construction like ``std::conditional_t<noconvert, nop>()``. The downside of this is adding further attributes and flags to ``function_record``.

Another alternative would be to it in ``cpp_function::initialize_generic`` by analyzing the function signature. I tried this as well, but it seemed brittle.

Thoughts?

Wenzel

